they call themselves ``the steeple people,'' and their creations can be found reaching for the sky from alaska to saudi arabia
jerry bennett has been one of them since his college days when he took a part-time job to help pay for his education. today, at 48, he is president and co-owner
there aren't many things we can't do when it comes to steeples,'' said bennett. ``we also specialize in cupolas, crosses, towers, or anything else needed to decorate a church or a building.''
campbellsville industries' products are shipped everywhere and may range from six feet to 229-feet, which is the size of what bennett calls the world's largest prefabricated steeple
we're trying to get it included in the guinness book of records,'' bennett said, adding that the $350,000 project was built for the first baptist church of huntsville, ala
other installations include the baptist pavilion at the 1982 world's fair in knoxville; the solidarity tower replica in chicago; and reproduction of the west bridgewater, mass., steeple, which was originally constructed during paul revere's time
the order from saudi arabia called for a cupola for a waterworks system.''
bennett's plant, located 80 miles from louisville, has 85 employees, including six draftsmen who will furnish a design if the customer doesn't know in advance what he wants
the company mails out more than one million pieces of advertising annually, but bennett said he also gets sales from the interstates
somebody will see our trucks, loaded with steeples or cupolas, and then telephone us to ask, `how do i get one of those things?' ''
his crews do a lot of driving. several years ago, they made four 1,200 mile trips to new haven, conn., to erect a spire on a roman catholic landmark there
bennett became involved with steeples after campbellsville college set up a small industry complex on campus to help students with their finances
i was among those who were able to work with wood or metal, turning out items that could be marketed for a nominal profit.''
later, bennett taught art in high school but returned to the college as a full-time employee handling designs and sales for the complex
in 1969, campbellsville college sold the business to a private individual who kept it 10 years before he was bought out by bennett and three other employees
although the company is diversified, steeples still account for 60 to 70 percent of sales. they also have caused a few embarrassing moments
bennett recalled the time that a contractor in virginia purchased a steeple and gave ``our deliveryman vague instructions about reaching the church where it was to be installed.''
the spire went to another church and the contractor showed up the next morning to retrieve it
before he could say anything, the excited minister told him:
we have been praying for new pews and an anonymous donor provided them
we prayed for new carpet and got it anonymously
the last item we wanted was a new steeple. last night, the lord put it in our front yard.''
the contractor explained the mixup and admitted later to bennett that ``it was the hardest thing i've ever done.''
oil prices remain mostly lower amid sluggish demand and adequate supplies
at the new york mercantile exchange, contracts for march delivery of west texas intermediate, the benchmark u.s. crude oil, closed wednesday at $16.61 per 41-gallon barrel, down 6 cents from tuesday
among refined products, wholesale contracts for unleaded gasoline closed at 46.66 cents a gallon, up 0.37 cent, while wholesale heating oil was down 0.79 cent at 45.58 cents a gallon
a trade report published late tuesday stimulated an early rally, because the numbers showed sharp drawdowns of gasoline and heating oil supplies, as well as a cutback of refinery use in the week ended friday, analysts said
they said the figures _ released by the washington-based american petroleum institute _ led many traders to believe that prices would increase, as existing demand chased tigher supplies
but the gains turned into losses, ``once people realized that the stocks were moving from primary storage into secondary storage in anticipation of the tugboat strike in new york harbor,'' said donald morton, an analyst at the boston office of prudential-bache securities inc
the market closed at its low in fairly light volume,'' he added
morton said dealers were having the products shipped from new york to boston and other markets to ensure continued access
a union representing 2,500 tugboat and barge crew members went on strike against nine towing companies on tuesday
northwest airlines' 6,500 flight attendants will vote to strike on feb. 26 if they haven't reached agreement on a new contract, teamsters union officials say
about 300 flight attendants with the eagan, minn.-based airline began the strike authorization vote tuesday during a union meeting in bloomington. results of the voting, which will continue through saturday in minneapolis and st. paul, minn., and five other u.s. cities, are expected to be announced at a strike rally monday night, teamsters local 2747 officials said wednesday
strike authorization requires a two-thirds majority of the membership
in the last strike against northwest, the machinists union walked out for 27 days in may 1982
the two sides have not negotiated since the national mediation board released them from mandatory negotiations last month because they were deadlocked over wages, fringe benefits and work rules. a 30-day cooling-off period ends feb. 26
a federal mediator is expected to bring the two sides together again next week, although no date has been set
northwest officials said they are determined to keep flying if a strike occurs. about 2,000 northwest managers are qualified to be flight attendants and would be used during a strike, said northwest spokesman redmond tyler. northwest also has advertised to recruit replacement flight attendants over the past few weeks
but some travel agents are beginning to warn prospective northwest passengers of a possible strike
people are starting to ask about it, '' said kevin mossier, president of the travel co., a minneapolis-st. paul travel agency
northwest, which merged with republic airlines in 1986, controls about 60 percent of the minneapolis-st. paul passenger traffic. in the event of a strike, united airlines, the no. 2 carrier in the twin cities, would bring in larger planes for twin cities flights, according to united spokesman matt gonring in chicago
on tuesday, a federal judge in new york city ordered the teamsters local to reinstate northwest flight attendants guy meek and john davis as members of the union's negotiating committee. meek and davis formerly worked for republic
the teamsters must allow the two men to participate in negotiations and vote on whether to send any contract offers to the flight attendants for ratification, u.s. district judge joseph mclaughlin ruled
teamsters officials had ejected the two men from the bargaining committee last fall, alleging that they tried to persuade 2,800 former republic attendants not to pay union dues
former republic attendants said the teamsters have urged them to pay union dues voluntarily
it was not clear from the judge's order whether the teamsters can force the members to pay dues, but teamsters spokesman jeff musto said all flight attendants would be allowed to vote on the strike authorization whether or not they were current on dues
on another front tuesday, a federal judge in minneapolis said northwest and its machinists union will have to arbitrate a 1{-year-old dispute over restoration of wage cuts granted by about 1,200 former republic airlines employees
u.s. district judge david doty dismissed a lawsuit brought by district lodge 143 of the international association of machinists in november 1986 and refused to order northwest to pay the higher wages
the dispute, which involves mechanics, stock clerks, plane cleaners, custodians and clerical workers who granted wage concessions to republic, should be resolved by an arbitrator, not a federal judge, doty ruled
black &amp; decker corp. has been rebuffed again in its attempt to make personal contact with the top management of american standard inc., which is the target of a takeover bid by black &amp; decker
in a filing wednesday with the securities and exchange commission, the power tool and home appliance maker said chairman nolan b. archibald attempted to telephone american standard chairman william b. boyd on feb. 11
unfortunately, as has been the case throughout, mr. boyd wouldn't take the call,'' said black &amp; decker spokeswoman barbara lucas
archibald wanted to reconfirm his company's ``strong desire to arrange a one-on-one meeting with mr. boyd to negotiate a business combination between black &amp; decker and the company, and to advise mr. boyd that he was willing to make major concessions in order to consummate a friendly transaction, including a preemptive price, board seats and financial arrangements for employees of the company,'' ms. lucas said
the message was no different from the one we've been leaving all along,'' she said
we think the price of $65 (a share) was a preemptive price,'' she said. the towson, md.-based manufacturer will consider raising that price, ``only on the basis of information that we haven't seen yet.''
however, the sec filing should not be taken as a sign that black &amp; decker is willing to raise the price, she stressed
american standard has urged its shareholders to reject black &amp; decker's $2.1 billion hostile takeover. the new york-based maker of plumbing, heating and air conditioning equipment has also adopted a ``poison pill'' defense that allows its shareholders to buy back shares of the surviving company at half their market value
american standard also has said it is considering alternatives to the bid, including a restructuring, leveraged buyout or a friendly merger with another company
black &amp; decker, which originally bid $56 a share for american standard stock, said last week it had obtained bank financing for the deal
the president of the association of flight attendants urged the federal aviation administration to tighten its regulation of the airline industry
passengers' first priority should be to insist that the faa promote safety over profit, rebuild the inspector workforce and place tighter controls on the number of flights until the air traffic controller workforce is rebuilt,'' susan bianchi-sand said at a news conference wednesday
ms. bianchi-sand proposed reforms that she said were inexpensive ways to improve cabin safety
all that is needed is a will to make flying truly safe,'' the union president said. ``we have learned from emergency after emergency that changes are needed.''
ms. bianchi-sand said the faa should update its standards to require passenger seats that do not break loose in a crash, require life vests on more planes, and limit the hours that flight attendants can work
ms. bianchi-sand said the faa also should resist industry pressure to repeal a ruling that would require improved cabin materials and reduce the threat of toxic smoke
where costs are involved, the industry is almost shameless,'' she said
campeau corp. has intensified the pressure on federated department stores inc. by boosting its tender offer for the giant retailer to $61 a share
federated, meanwhile, continued to look into ways of avoiding a hostile takeover
campeau's amended offer came wednesday a day after the federated board of directors rejected the toronto developer's previous proposal to pay $66 a share in a definitive merger agreement. the board had questioned whether campeau had the necessary financial backing to complete the $5.85 billion deal
campeau said it would further sweeten its bid to $66 if federated agreed to be acquired by midnight sunday. the company was only willing to pay $66 a share if federated management agreed to go along voluntarily. campeau is offering a lower price if federated management resists
instead of accepting the tender offer, the federated directors decided on a restructuring that could include retaining federated's department stores and selling its other assets, the company said
the latest rebuff by federated's directors did not deter campeau, which said wednesday it has the necessary financing to buy federated
campeau's latest tender offer of $61 a share amounts to about $5.4 billion, a sharp increase from the $47 a share, or roughly $4.2 billion, it initially offered on jan. 25. federated rejected the original tender offer as inadequate
federated stock fell $2 to $61.75 a share in new york stock exchange trading wednesday
federated also twice rejected campeau's alternative offer for a definitive merger agreement, including offers of $61 and $66 per share, because it questioned campeau's ability to complete such a deal
however, campeau spokeswoman joele frank said in new york wednesday that ``financing for a $66 bid is absolutely solid.''
federated managers are looking into other options, such as selling to other unspecified interested parties, issuing perferred stock and buying back more than half of federated's 88.5 million shares
analysts said it was unclear how federated might proceed if it chooses to sell its non-department store assets
a lot depends on whether they sell them to someone outright or spin them off'' through a public stock offering, said thomas tashjian, an analyst with the los angeles investment firm of seidler amdec securities inc
federated operates about 650 stores in 36 states and had sales exceeding $11 billion last year. its holdings include bloomingdale's and abraham and straus, both based in new york; filene's of boston; burdines of miami; rich's in atlanta; bullock's and bullock's-wilshire in los angeles; i. magnin in san francisco; and lazarus in ohio
the company could be considering selling chains such as its ralphs grocery stores, main street soft-goods stores, gold circle discount stores and children's place clothing stores, industry observers said
federated's directors said a shareholders' rights plan adopted by the board last month would take effect thursday. the plan, known as a ``poison pill'' defense, is designed to discourage an unwanted takeover by making such a move more expensive
federated spent last weekend negotiating with numerous parties, including campeau, which bought allied stores corp. in december 1986. among those believed to be interested is the takeover specialist firm kohlberg, kravis, roberts &amp; co., based in new york
campeau's upgraded tender offer wednesday includes a provision that recently enacted anti-takeover legislation would have to be invalidated. campeau is challenging anti-takeover measures in delaware and ohio
cincinnati-based federated could be covered by both anti-takeover measures because it is based in ohio and is incorporated in delaware
britain's unemployment rate fell to a seasonally adjusted 9.2 percent of the workforce in january from 9.4 percent in the previous month, the department of labor said thursday
last month's figure also was down from 11.2 percent in january 1987
the latest rate was the lowest since november 1981, when the jobless rate was also 9.2 percent. the number of jobless has declined for 18 consecutive months, the department said
total seasonally adjusted unemployment was estimated at 2.56 million people in january, down from a revised 2.61 million people in december and 3.11 million people a year ago. arabia</head>
texaco inc. plans to sell a stake of about 50 percent in its extensive u.s. gulf coast refining operations to saudi arabia for more than $1 billion, according to the international herald tribune
a final agreement between petromin, the saudi arabian oil holding arm, and texaco is expected to be reached within a month, the herald tribune reported thursday, quoting an unidentified texaco executive and unidentified arab oil executives attending an annual conference of the institute of petroleum in london
in white plains, n.y., a spokesman at texaco's headquarters refused to confirm or deny the accuracy of the report
on jan. 8, texaco announced as part of its restructuring plan that it would aggressively move foward to get partners in joint ventures based on its downstream operations,'' said k. peter maneri. ``at this stage, it would be inappropriate to issue public statement regarding those discussions.''
saudi arabia has been considering taking a large stake in the refining and marketing arms of one of the u.s. major oil companies which were once shareholders in the arabian american oil co., or aramco, oil industry officials said
those companies are chevron corp., exxon corp. mobil corp., and texaco
over the past few months, all four companies have been given preferential access to saudi arabia's crude oil at market-related prices, which are below officials prices, while most other companies have had to pay official prices for the oil
texaco has been the largest single buyer of saudi crude oil for the past year, oil industry sources said
texaco announced its restructuring program as part of its plan for emerging from chapter 11 bankruptcy protection
the nation's third-largest oil company hopes to complete that move in april, one year after it filed for protection from its creditors to avoid having to post a potentially ruinous bond while appealing a $10.3 billion judgement held against the company by pennzoil co
a houston jury awarded the judgement to pennzoil after ruling that texaco had improperly interfere with a pennzoil plan to acquire part of getty oil co. and acquired getty itself
as part of its proposed reorganization plan, texaco agreed to settle the case by paying pennzoil $3 billion in cash
japan has made satisfactory moves to regulate its stock and futures markets to curb insider trading, the chairman of the u.s. securities and exchange commission said thursday
i think the japanese are moving at a good pace toward insider trading restrictions,'' said david s. ruder, who arrived here this week at the invitation of japanese officials for talks on improving cooperation to guard against insider trading and cope with market volatility
i have had a great sense of a desire for cooperation between the american and the japanese stock markets, futures markets and regulators,'' he said
the sec, which regulates the u.s. securities industry, and japan's finance ministry issued a joint statement wednesday saying both sides had agreed to strengthen measures against insider trading and improve communication between exchanges in both countries
the statement came a day after the finance ministry recommended in a report stronger measures against insider trading on par with those in the united states. the report said japan's securities and exchange law should be tightened to specifically prohibit insider trading and recommended that criminal penalties replace current civil penalties for such abuses
ruder said the proposal ``seemed to cover the elements of insider trading as we know it in the corporate environment in the united states.''
wednesday's joint statement vowed to encourage discussions between self-regulatory organizations in both countries to detect fraudulent activity and develop ``procedures for the exchange of financial, surveillance and investigatory information among those organizations.''
restrictions on insider trading, ruder said, must be approached carefully because of a conflict between preventing inside corporate information from leaking to the public and a desire to encourage public disclosure of certain information
the infrequency of corporate takeovers in japan helps prevent large-scale insider trading, he said. knowledge of a planned takeover before its public disclosure is a key reason for insider trading, as it creates an opportunity to buy stocks of a target company and often sell them at a higher price later
but financial sources have said information is often leaked to investors in the japanese market
japan's big four securities firms _ nomura, nikko, daiwa and yamaichi _ can handle as much as 80 percent of daily stock trading volume, creating an environment for market manipulation, financial sources say
until october's worldwide stock market crash led the tokyo stock exchange to impose rules on reporting transactions, japanese executives were not required to report transfers of their shareholdings
the sec and finance ministry recognized a growing ``interlinkage'' between markets in both countries and agreed that planned expansion of futures trading in japan will intensify their interdependence, ruder said
he also said communication between the u.s. and japanese markets would be improved after the u.s. commodities futures trading commission is put in direct contact with the finance ministry's securities bureau
in talks this week, the ministry and the sec agreed to create safeguards to counter ``market emergencies,'' their joint statement said
market volatility, as experienced in october 1987, becomes even more a global concern,'' ruder said, and praised the caution exercised by japanese institutional investors in times of crisis
stock prices in new york fell about 23 percent on black monday, but the nikkei stock average, the tokyo market's key indicator, followed with a fall of less than 15 percent partly because japanese institutional investors were reluctant to flee the market, ruder said
i think i will go back to give the message to institutional investors that they should be more cautious in their reactions, like japanese investors,'' he said. surface</head> congress; picks up 2nd graf pvs: the commerce ...</note>
president reagan sent congress a $1.09 trillion conciliatory, election-year budget today that combines his most restrained military request ever with proposals for more spending on education, science and the fight against aids
reagan's 1989 budget, the last budget of his presidency, calls for reducing the federal deficit from $150.2 billion last year and the $146.7 billion estimated for 1988 to $129.5 billion in the fiscal year that begins next oct. 1
that is below the target of $136 billion called for in the gramm-rudman deficit-reduction law
the new budget also contends that the ``economy has shown few signs of serious damage'' from last october's stock market plunge, and that the recent boom in exports holds out the promise of continued economic expansion
but signs of economic weakness were evident in the government's reports that housing construction fell in january while industrial production rose at a slower rate than in each of the previous two months, some analysts say
the commerce department said wednesday that housing construction fell 1.9 percent to its slowest pace since the end of the last recession five years ago
separately, the federal reserve board said industrial production rose 0.2 percent in january after 0.4 percent gains in november and december
the report on construction of single-family homes and apartments raised new concerns among some economists about the possibility of a recession this year
the january decline in housing construction followed a 15.5 percent december tumble and pushed building activity down to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 1.38 million units, the slowest pace since a rate of 1.3 million units in december 1982, just as the last recession was ending
housing is being watched very closely in the aftermath of the stock market crash last october because it is often one of the first sectors to weaken at the onset of a new recession
the weakness last month came from a 2.9 percent decline in construction of single-family homes, which fell to an annual rate of 1.01 million units
this drop offset a 0.8 percent increase in construction of multi-family housing, which edged up to an annual rate of 366,000 units
building permits, considered a good sign of future activity, fell 8.2 percent in january to an annual rate of 1.25 million units, the lowest level for permits since january 1985. permits had fallen 7.4 percent in december
in a separate report, a private forecasting firm estimated that construction contracts will drop 4 percent this year, led by steep declines in office and other commercial building and lesser drops in housing and public works projects
builders will commit to $246.2 billion worth of new contracts in all of 1988 compared with $255.2 billion last year, according to an update of the 1988 dodge-sweet's construction outlook from mcgraw-hill information systems co
private analysts said the slower growth in industrial production may indicate the economy will slow in the early part of 1988 as businesses work off a backlog of unsold inventories built up during the final three months of 1987
the federal reserve traced the output rise in january to production of non-durable goods, which rose 0.4 percent. production of durable goods, items expected to last three years, showed no increase last month
in a budget that calls for few tax changes, president reagan today recommended a tax break to help parents save to pay for a college education for their children
the president, in submitting his 1989 budget to congress, said he will ask lawmakers to make tax-exempt the interest on savings bonds that are redeemed to finance post-secondary education. this would cost the government an estimated $10 million during the 12 months beginning next oct. 1
the tax benefit would be targeted for lower- and middle-income families and would be eliminated as earnings exceed a certain level
the costs of post-secondary education have increased substantially in recent years, often faster than inflation,'' reagan said in his written message to congress. ``as a result, parents may have difficulty bearing these costs unless they establish a savings program for this purpose when their children are young.''
the biggest new revenue-raiser recommended by the president would require all state and local government employees to pay the medicare hospital-insurance tax. the tax, which most americans already pay, is 1.45 percent of the first $45,000 earned. the levy is collected as part of the social security tax
the tax already is collected from state and local workers hired after march 31, 1986. reagan said workers hired before that date also should be required to pay in order to reduce a drain on the medicare system
the change, which congress has rejected several times, would bring in $1.6 billion in 1989
repeal of the ``windfall-profit'' tax on the oil industry, which congress also has rejected, is included in the president's budget. reagan says the tax, which was imposed when oil prices were rising, is an unnecessary paperwork burden on the industry at a time of declining prices
the oil industry would get a $52-million tax break under the budget if congress goes along with a proposed modification of rules affecting the depletion allowance
other revenue proposals:
_a permanent tax break for owners of shares in mutual funds, who would be affected by a 1986 tax change that limits miscellaneous itemized deductions to those that exceed 2 percent of adjusted gross income. congress voted an exception to mutual-fund deductions for 1987 only
_permit u.s. companies to allocate at least two-thirds of their total research and development expenditures to domestic operations. this would save them about $600 million in 1989
_make permanent a temporary tax credit for research and experimentation, saving u.s. companies $400 million next year
_repeal a provision imposed by congress that reduces air-ticket taxes and aviation-fuel levies when federal spending for airport and airways imporovements drops below a certain level
_increase user fees incurred in federal regulation of nuclear power plants
_change the method of calculating a special fee on imported products, costing the government about $100 million next year. the modification of the 0.17-percent fee is necessary to bring the united states into compliance with international trade agreements. include morgan reaction. picks up 3rd graf pvs, moody's also ...</note>
a major wall street debt analyzer has lowered its credit ratings for eight of the nation's biggest banking institutions because of a decline in its valuation of their foreign loans
the action wednesday by moody's investors service comes 15 days after another credit ratings service, standard &amp; poor's corp., lowered its estimate of the creditworthiness of five big banking companies
among the banking concerns downgraded by moody's was j.p. morgan &amp; co., which lost its top rating. at the same time, moody's affirmed its top rating for morgan's banking unit, morgan guaranty trust co
in a statement, the company said it was disappointed that the rating of the holding company ``does not appear to recognize fully our exceptional capital position and our capacity to repay all debt without reliance on any dividends from morgan guaranty.''
moody's also said it had confirmed its ratings for three banking companies and was continuing to review its rating on debt from a 12th banking concern, european american bank corp
the ratings help determine interest rate levels for companies borrowing money in the credit markets and apply to securities of various maturities. a lower rating often means a company may have to pay more interest to sell debt
the downgradings affected about $48 billion in outstanding debt, while the confirmations applied to about $34.6 billion in debt, moody's said
roger arner, senior analyst at moody's, said the action followed a review begun last december of loans that a dozen major banking companies and their subsidiaries had outstanding to third world countries
moody's had previously indicated that some third world countries, including brazil, argentina and venezuela, were becoming economically less capable and politically less willing to continue servicing their debt as agreed
arner said moody's review indicated that some banking institutions continued to carry some third world loans on their books at a higher value than the ratings concern felt was warranted
we think their assets are worth less. we think banks will continue to need to build their capital and that our ratings are reflective of our assesment of their ability to do that,'' he said
the ratings cuts generally ranged from one to three steps on the agency's 10-step system for investment quality ratings, depending on moody's assessment of the varying earnings potential, capital and assets of each of the concerns
the eight downgrades included j.p. morgan & co.; bankers trust co.; citibank n.a.; chase manhattan corp.; chemical new york corp.; manufacturers hanover corp.; bankamerica corp.; and irving trust co
the three ratings confirmations were for first chicago corp., continental illinois corp. and bank of nova scotia
moody's took different approaches in some cases on its ratings of debt issued by a bank holding company and that by its subsidiary bank
while lowering the rating for citibank, for instance, moody's confirmed its rating for the parent company, citicorp. citibank is the nation's biggest bank and citicorp is the nation's biggest bank holding company
on feb. 2, standard &amp; poor's said it was lowering its rating on debt from chase manhattan corp., bankamerica corp., chemical new york corp., manufacturers hanover corp. and first chicago corp., citing third world loans
at the same time, it affirmed its ratings for citicorp, bankers trust new york corp. and j.p. morgan &amp; co
many major banking companies reported losses or sharply diminished earnings in 1987 as they boosted their loan-loss reserves, which provide a cushion for future earnings against loans that may be written off or sold at a loss
but arner said moody's viewed some of those actions as ``accounting transfers'' that the agency felt ``have not added any real strength to the balance sheet.''
the reagan administration today issued an economic forecast any republican presidential candidate could run on with pride, predicting a record sixth year of peacetime economic growth with no increase in inflation
the administration, which in the past has been derided for its ``rosy scenarios'' of future economic activity, presented an optimistic view that the current expansion will continue into the indefinite future. and it derided initial recession fears from the october stock market crash as ``greatly exaggerated.''
despite the sharp reversal in stock prices, however, the real economy has shown few signs of serious damage,'' the budget forecast stated
while the economic assumptions that underpin the president's 1989 budget are more optimistic than the predictions made by the congressional budget office and most private forecasters, they are not as far from the general consensus as in previous years
indeed, the administration boasts that its economic forecast a year ago, which was also above the general consensus, turned out to be closer to right
the economy, as measured by the gross national product, grew 3.8 percent in 1987, when measured from the fourth quarter of 1986. the administration had predicted 3.2 percent growth
most forecasters failed to anticipate the magnitude of the improvement in the manufacturing sector just then getting under way,'' the budget stated
for 1988, the administration predicts manufacturing will remain a source of strength with export sales continuing to rise because of the weaker dollar
the administration predicts the overall economy will expand at a 2.4 percent annual rate this year with much of that growth coming from the improving trade deficit
this compares to a cb0 growth forecast of 1.8 percent. the cbo forecast is the same as the consensus view of 51 top economists surveyed by blue chip economic indicators, an investment newsletter
among the economic assumptions, the administration predicts:
_gnp growth will rebound in 1989 to a 3.5 percent rate and stay above 3 percent through 1993
_consumer inflation, which rose 4.4 percent last year, will rise by 4.3 percent this year and decline steadily over the next four years to a 2 percent rate in 1993
_unemployment, because of the modest growth, will show no improvement this year, remaining at 5.8 percent at the close of the year, matching the current level. however, the jobless rate will begin declining modestly in future years, dropping to 5.5 percent in 1989
these assumptions provide the basis for the administration's hopes of making further progress in getting the federal budget under control
the 1989 spending plan, reagan's eighth submission to congress, has a valedictory quality about it, reviewing in detail the president's economic goals when he took office in 1981 and trying to explain the reasons for reagan's biggest economic failure, the string of record budget deficits
the administration, as it has in the past, put much of the blame on congress for failing to enact its domestic spending cuts. but the budget also says the 1981-82 deficit played a large role, adding $112 billion to the deficit in 1983 alone
the new budget calls for reducing the federal deficit to $129.5 billion in the fiscal year that begins next oct. 1, down from an actual budget deficit of $150.2 billion in the 1987 fiscal year and an estimated deficit of $146.7 billion for the current fiscal year
the 1987 deficit was originally put at $148 billion but was revised in today's budget document
the 1989 budget estimate is below the target of $136 billion called for in the gramm-rudman deficit-reduction law, but the administration concedes that its estimates in the past have fallen victim to worse-than-expected economic performance
those pitfalls could derail the current plan as well, the administration says, noting that if gnp growth is just 1 percent lower than the administration is forecasting over the next five years it would add $6.3 billion to the 1989 deficit and $66 billion to the 1993 deficit
a minority of economists is predicting an even worse outcome for this year, forecasting the economy will fall into an actual recession
if growth is slower than the administration forecasts, or in a worst-case scenario, the country does enter a recession, then that would mean smaller federal tax revenues and higher spending for such programs as unemployment benefits
the current economic recovery began in december 1982, following the worst recession since the great depression, and is now in its 63rd month, surpassing the old record for a peacetime recovery of 59 months set between 1975 and 1979
the stock market declined slightly today in sluggish trading
the dow jones average of 30 industrials dropped 1.98 to 1,999.01 in the first half hour
losers outnumbered gainers by about 7 to 6 in the early tally of new york stock exchange-listed issues, with 466 up, 552 down and 497 unchanged
