early returns in voting today by 32,000 striking empoyees from ford motor co.'s british plants indicated strong approval of a new two-year contract, the company said
we are greatly encouraged by the voting figures coming in,'' said a ford spokesman who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``there have been some big swings in favor of accepting the offer, compared to voting on the last offer, which was turned down.''
the final results were to be released on friday, but the spokesman said hourly workers from at least eight of ford's 22 british plants voted to accept the contract
the strike, which began feb. 8, prompted the layoff of more than 9,700 workers. it disrupted production at a ford plant at genk, belgium, and threatened production at ford plants in spain and west germany, which rely on parts made at the british plants
the settlement was worked out in negotiations tuesday between company and union officials. if accepted, operations at ford's british plants could resume monday
shop stewards representing 8,000 ford workers at the traditionally militant halewood plant near liverpool in northwest england on wednesday recommended rejection of the offer
peter moore, a local union official at halewood, said: ``we feel there should be more money on offer, but we are also concerned that plants on the continent are getting improvements in hours and holidays and we won't be getting that for another two years.''
shop stewards at a ford engine-manufacturing plant in bridgend, wales, recommended acceptance, saying they believed the company had made significant concessions. that plant employs 1,300 hourly workers
the financial times, britain's leading business daily, said in today's editions that the strikers seemed set to accept the deal, although possibly by a narrow margin. the british broadcasting corp. said the deal appeared likely to gain at least 60 percent support
ford backed down on its demand for a three-year contract, offering instead a two-year pact with wage increases of at least 14 percent over the term of the contract. a ford assembly worker in britain now earns a basic $320 a week
the unions agreed to changes in working practices designed to increase productivity, but the changes must be agreed upon at the plant level instead of being imposed by management
legislator barry porter of prime minister margaret thatcher's governing conservative party on wednesday condemned the proposed settlement
it is quite clear that other industrial unions will take this climbdown by the management as their bench mark for their claims in the future. this has national implications in relation to the government's fight against inflation,'' he said
britain's annual inflation rate is now 3.3 percent. this is the lowest it has been since october 1986
the government introduced tough measure to curb the once powerful unions and the last major industrial strike in britain was a yearlong walkout by more than 90,000 coal miners in 1984-1985
but the ford strike, a walkout by english channel ferry crews, and unrest in the state-run national health service and elsewhere prompted fears in some quarters that they could herald a new wave of industrial strife and an explosion in pay demands
ford's british workers last walked out for nine weeks in 1978
