grain and soybean futures opened mostly lower today on the chicago board of trade
soybean prices fell on profit-taking from wednesday's sharp gains and in reaction to an increase in farmer selling of soybeans, analysts said
soybean futures advanced as much as 13} cents a bushel wednesday, partly in reaction to a paul harvey radio commentary about a ``sudden-death syndrome'' affecting soybean crops. the story turned out to be based on research findings that were first reported nearly two years ago
speculative buying limited the losses in soybeans this morning, said richard loewy, senior grain and oilseed analyst for the investment firm prudential-bache securities inc. in new york
the market's not breaking as much as it could have, so there's some underlying strength,'' loewy said
corn prices also retreated on increased farmer sales, while wheat prices declined in follow-through selling from wednesday, analysts said
in early trading, wheat was } cent to 1{ cents lower with the contract for delivery in march at $3.26\ a bushel; corn was } cent to 2\ cents lower with march at $2.00\ a bushel; oats were } cent lower to { cent higher with march at $1.91 a bushel; soybeans were 2{ cents to 3{ cents lower with march at $6.30 a bushel
