live cattle futures advanced on wednesday while other livestock and meat futures settled mostly lower
lomas &amp; nettleton financial corp., citing a downturn in the nation's housing market, says it plans to shut down half its mortgage banking operations and cut about 20 percent of its workforce
the dallas company, which is the nation's largest independent mortgage banker, said it would take a $93 million charge in the current quarter as a result of its restructuring plans
lomas said it expects to lose about $69 million for the three fiscal quarters ended march 31 and about $55 million for the year
lomas president james wooten said wednesday that the company planned to close offices in more than 30 of the 65 cities in which its mortgage branch operates, and lay off 500 of its 2,650 employees. the company also cut nearly 1,000 employees last year
although final decisions have not been made on which offices to eliminate, several are expected to be in the midwest and southeast, wooten said
the company also said it plans to divest itself of a small, virtually inactive home-building company, braewood homes of dallas
lomas' problems stem from a downturn in the housing industry nationwide, which has slowed new mortgage originations
the mortgage bankers association, a trade group, estimates there will be between $320 billion and $330 billion in mortgages originated nationwide in 1988, a decline from the $430 billion originated in 1987
at the same time, more homeowners have fallen behind on their payments, and more of the company's existing loans are delinquent, wooten said
by far the biggest portion of it (the restructuring) is the result of bankruptcies and foreclosures that have just kept on keeping on,'' he said. ``rather than whittle it as you go, you've got to build a reserve for it and start recovering from it.''
kenneth campbell, an analyst with audit investments inc. of montvale, n.j., said lomas is not alone in its troubles
other mortgage bankers are seeing the same thing. they've either cut back on offices or staffing. the whole industry has been slammed into reverse,'' he said
midland bank plc, one of britain's big four commercial banks, said thursday it suffered a huge loss during 1987, due to the october stock market crash and its decision to raise its loan-loss provision to cover shaky third world debt
the bank said it lost 456 million pounds, or about $798 million, last year, compared with a net profit of about $424 million in 1986
midland took a charge of $1.79 billion in the middle of last year for an increase in its loan-loss provisions. but it said an extraordinary gain of $110 million, on which it wouldn't elaborate, helped narrow the 1987 loss
excluding the loan-loss provision charge, midland said, its pre-tax profit would have been about $894 million
several major u.s. banks also reported a severe drop in 1987 earnings or losses due to their decision to build up provisions for loan losses. the banks' goal was to establish a cushion to protect future earnings from loans that must be writen off or disposed of at a loss
the action was taken after brazil, the developing world's biggest debtor, halted interest payments on its international bank debt a year ago. the banks also cited continuing economic woes in third wrold countries and a series of debt restructurings
midland also said ``losses incurred by (the) institutional equities business were ... a serious setback, but we believe our investment banking operations as a whole weathered the financial storms of 1987, especially the period since october,'' when worldwide equity markets collapsed
midland said it began a cost-cutting program at the end of last year
in november, the bank announced that hongkong &amp; shanghai banking corp. would take a 14.9 percent stake in midland and that the two banks would collaborate on a number of activities
last summer, the company sold additional stock. reaction</note>
president reagan today sent congress a $1.09 trillion conciliatory, election-year budget combining his most restrained military request ever with proposals for more spending on education, science and the fight against aids
in presenting this budget, i am keeping my end of the bargain. i call upon congress to uphold its end,'' reagan said in the eighth, and for practical purposes, final budget of his presidency
unlike earlier reagan budgets, the new document embodies an agreement on spending priorities already reached with congress
reagan's 1989 budget calls for reducing the federal deficit from $150.2 billion last year and the $146.7 billion estimated for 1988 to $129.5 billion in the fiscal year that begins next oct. 1
that's even below the target of $136 billion called for in the gramm-rudman deficit-reduction law. when reagan took office in 1981 with a promise to balance the budget within three years the annual deficit stood at $78 billion
at a white house photo session with congressional leaders, reagan extolled the budget for not increasing taxes while increasing spending to battle illicit drugs and aids
with a pile of blue budget documents stacked before him on the table, reagan said he hoped the white house and congress ``can work together through this budget process this year, sticking to our agreement and completing the appropriation process before the end of this fiscal year.''
leaving a white house meeting with reagan, the democrats who head the house and senate budget committees said the budget was better than past reagan efforts. sen. lawton chiles, r-fla., said, ``i think it's a good faith budget. it looks like it meets the (budget) summit agreements. it's right at the targets.'' but chiles said congress would not agree to sell off so many government assets as reagan wants
the house budget chairman, rep. william h. gray, d-pa., said, ``there are some better domestic priorities than in the past. however, there still are some problems areas, such as the willingness to build more houses in space as opposed to housing here on earth.''
in today's budget message, reagan conceded the new document ``does not fully reflect my priorities, nor, presumably, those of any particular member of congress.''
but, citing ``give and take on all sides,'' reagan told congress: ``the goal of deficit reduction through spending reduction must be paramount.''
the two-year budget pact struck with congress last november, in the wake of the stock market collapse, sets limits for both military increases and social program cuts and restricts new taxes to the $14 billion already passed for 1989 by congress
because of this prior agreement, reagan's fiscal 1989 budget was expected to generate few fireworks on arrival at capitol hill. and budget leaders played down prospects of a major election-year budget fracas
the new reagan budget contends that the ``economy has shown few signs of serious damage'' from last october's stock market plunge, and that the recent boom in exports holds out the promise of continued economic expansion
in fact, the new reagan budget assumes a declining rate of inflation, falling interest rates and economic growth of 2.4 percent this year and 3.5 percent next year. this projection is more optimistic than forecasts by congressional budget analysts and private forecasters but closer to their predictions than in previous years
however, if growth is even one percentage point less than reagan's forecast, the deficit would rise an additional $6.3 billion in 1989 and $18 billion in 1990, the budget report conceded
reagan's new budget proposed military spending authority of $299.5 billion in fiscal 1989 and actual outlays for the year of $294 billion _ up from $291.4 billion in 1988 in budget authority and $285.4 billion in outlays
that increase, which doesn't even keep pace with last year's 4.4 percent increase in inflation, represents the smallest military spending increase ever sent to congress by reagan. it is likely to result in reductions in some of the military forces and weapons programs that have grown substantially since he became president
anything less would jeopardize not only our security ... but would also dim the prospects for further negotiated agreements with our adversaries,'' reagan said
reagan's budget recycles a number of favorite administration proposals for reducing government programs
these include the abolition of the interstate commerce commission, the economic development administration, small business administration direct loans, urban development action grants and public subsidies for amtrak rail passenger service and mass transit systems
in addition, reagan again proposed the sale naval petroleum reserves and some regional power-marketing authorities _ including the alaska power administration
even though these ``privatization'' efforts have never gained much support in congress, reagan expanded the concept this year by proposing, for the first time, the sale of waste treatment plants, mass transit projects and the rural telephone bank. in addition, he asked for studies of ``possible privatization'' of some postal service operations and the government's uranium enrichment facilities
however, this year, the administration backed away from some of the more politically controversial proposals of past reagan budgets _ including abolition of the legal services corp. and sale of the bonneville power adminstration
at the same time, the president laced his 1989 request with a number of items certain to be politically palatable _ including nearly $2 billion in spending authority to combat ``the scourge of aids,'' a 38 percent increase over 1988 levels
in addition, reagan _ who last year caused congressional consternation by proposing sharp cuts in education spending _ proposed a $1.5 billion increase in education outlays, a rise of 8 percent, well over inflation
the new budget also earmarked $1.6 billion in spending authority to upgrade the nation's air control system and a $430 million increase for the ``superfund'' program to clean up hazardous waste sites
other new proposals for spending authority in reagan's 1989 budget:
_ a request for $437 million, more than double last year's budget, for federal prison constructon to relieve overcrowding
_ a 13 percent increase, to $3.9 billion, for drug law enforcement and treatment programs
_ a request for $11.5 billion for space programs, including the program to orbit a manned space station and to improve the ``performance and reliability'' of the space shuttle
_ spending of $363 million to begin construction of the superconducting super collider, ``the largest pure science project ever undertaken.''
_ stepped up law enforcement efforts, with a focus on white collar crime, organized crime and terrorism
_ full funding for a $2.5 billion, five-year program to combat acid rain
although the budget proposal would come in under the $136 billion deficit ceiling specified by the gramm-rudman law, part of the savings would be accomplished with the sale of federal assets _ including about $12 billion in federal loans
under the budget agreement, asset sales cannot be fully counted toward meeting the deficit reduction target. taking out these sales, the reagan budget would result in a deficit of about $143 billion
that would still be within the bounds allowed by the law, which says the 1989 deficit can be as high as $146 billion without triggering automatic spending cuts
prices on the london stock exchange fell thursday after a weak early trend on wall street compounded earlier worries about inflationary pressure on the british economy
the financial times-stock exchange 100-stock index closed down 12 points, or 0.69 percent, at 1736.1
the market was depressed during the morning by the release of economic data that pointed to increased inflationary pressure on the economy. the figures revived worries of a further increase in base lending rates
the market was especially concerned by an increase in bank lending last month
share prices fell to the day's low during the afternoon because of a weak early trend on wall street, dealers said
