the royale belge spokesman said his company still had a small stake in a societe generale unit sodecom, which is a vehicle for a contested share issue societe generale is trying to launch to dilute de benedetti's stake in the company. cases</head>
severe insider-trading penalties are damaging new cases by discouraging potential defendants from cooperating, a top official of the securities and exchange commission was quoted as saying thursday
gary lynch, sec enforcement director and one of the architects behind an aggressive campaign against wall street corruption, was quoted as saying in an interview that the prospect of imprisonment, civil fines and financial ruin is convincing some people ``it's better to hunker down than cooperate.''
it was unclear from lynch's remarks whether he was suggesting less stringent sanctions against insider trading, the illicit use of nonpublic information to profit in securities transactions
lynch spoke to ``the wall street journal report,'' a weekly television program of business and financial news produced by dow jones &amp; co., publisher of the wall street journal
the company released a partial transcript of his remarks, to be broadcast this sunday, one year since the feb. 20, 1987 sentencing of dennis b. levine, a former investment banker whose arrest for massive insider trading infractions spawned a widespread federal investigation
levine, who cooperated with the government, was forced to relinquish $11.6 million in illicit profits. he received a criminal punishment of two years imprisonment and a $362,000 fine
we're getting less cooperation today,'' lynch was quoted as saying in response to a question about what has changed in the past year that has made the investigation easier or more difficult
more people are asserting their fifth amendment rights and not cooperating,'' he was quoted as saying. ``so we're not able to ask basic questions about contact, and that's certainly their constitutional right, but it does make it more difficult to put together information for an investigation.''
asked for further explanation, lynch was quoted as saying: ``it was one thing when people had to be concerned about a civil action by the sec and perhaps the disgorgement of money
it's another thing, when you talk about putting them out of business completely and, not getting disgorgement of profits, but a civil penalty as well and then subjecting them to the possibility of time in federal prison. so, add it all up and some lawyers are advising their clients: it's better to hunker down than cooperate.''
lynch was traveling abroad until monday and unavailable to comment about the interview, his office said
sec spokeswoman mary mccue, who didn't attend the interview, said ``i've heard gary say before that there is more hunkering down, so i would not dispute that, but i don't know if i would make that the greatest news release that ever hit the pike.''
levine's cooperation led investigators to ivan f. boesky, once one of wall street's most powerful stock speculators. he paid a record $100 million to settle civil charges of insider trading in november 1986 and was sentenced to a three-year criminal term last december
although boesky and levine are said to have implicated a number of other wall street professionals in illegal activity, there have been no significant arrests in the past year
taiwanese trade concessions made under u.s. pressure are profoundly changing this prosperous island, enraging businessmen who face stiffer competition and delighting consumers who find lower price tags on foreign goods
the united states, which ran up a record trade deficit last year, has pressured taiwan to cut its hefty tariffs and revalue its currency. roughly one-tenth of the $171.2 billion u.s. deficit came from trade with taiwan
since the united states is taiwan's most important political ally and receives nearly half of taiwan's exports, washington's wishes cannot be ignored
we want to maintain our export market in the united states so we must take more positive measures to help solve the trade problems (between the two countries),'' economic affairs minister lee ta-hai told a recent legislative session
after decades of closely linking the taiwan dollar to the u.s. dollar, taiwan authorities have allowed their currency to rise about 40 percent against the u.s. dollar since january 1986
the changing exchange rate makes taiwan goods more expensive overseas and american products cheaper in taiwan
taiwan also recently reduced tariffs on 3,500 agricultural and industrial products in a sweeping move that cut the average duty on imported goods to an estimated 3.8 percent from 7.5 percent, although tariffs on some goods remain much higher
u.s. officials, however, have indicated they want even further trade concessions from taiwan and asia's other newly industrialized countries _ hong kong, singapore and south korea. that upsets taiwanese who believe the trade concessions already have hurt the country, whose exports account for 58 percent of gross national product
in a poll conducted by the mass-circulation china times and published at the end of 1987, about 350 people out of nearly 1,000 interviewed chose the united states as the most unfriendly nation to taiwan. that was more than double the number of people who picked communist china, taiwan's arch rival
our 40 years of endeavors may be wiped out in these one or two years,'' grumbled david hong, president of k-moebel co., a sporting goods manufacturer whose 140-member work force was cut in half to reduce costs as the rising taiwan dollar squeezed profits
hong said the united states' decision in january to remove duty-free and preferential tariffs on taiwan products would make business even more difficult
i am worried that mainland chinese products, which will continue to enjoy the preferential tariffs, may gradually take over,'' he said
businessmen argue that the taiwan government has made too many trade concessions too quickly under u.s. pressure, giving labor-intensive local industries little time to adjust
farmers also say the government has sacrificed their interests to please the united states by cutting tariffs on farm products. thousands of farmers descended on taipei last december to protest sharply lowered fruit prices
but taiwan's policy changes have not all been painful
taiwan citizens generally welcome the government's tariff cuts on a wide variety of foreign products, which have long been too expensive for most people to afford
an estimated 8,000 american passenger cars were sold to taiwan last year, an eightfold increase from the year before but still representing only 4 percent of the domestic market. total imported cars sales increased an estimated 35 percent
imports of some american home appliances and many other goods more than doubled last year. u.s. goods accounted for an estimated 5 percent of color televisions sold, 14 percent of refrigerators, 21 percent of washing machines and 8 percent of cigarettes
american cars are no longer considered as expensive, bulky and gasoline-consuming. many people are buying them now as the second family car,'' said auto dealer sherry yang
office managers, secretaries and salesmen armed with fatter paychecks are buying buicks, skyhawks and cieras that once were only within the reach of the most wealthy. a skyhawk sells for about 700,000 taiwan dollars, or $25,000, about 30 percent cheaper than two years ago
many people are finding for the first time they can afford american products,'' said dustine wang, a dealer of whirlpool, general electric and westinghouse home appliances, which used to be more than twice as expensive as local products
i did not hesitate at all in buying it,'' wu pei-pei said of her new whirlpool washer. ''i know it is more endurable, has a larger capacity and not much more expensive'' than her old taiwan-made machine
recent statistics indicate the trade gap is narrowing
taiwan's january trade surplus of $843 million with the united states was the lowest since february 1986
with its january exports of $1.2 billion, the united states replaced japan for the first time since 1963 as the country selling the most goods to taiwan
but the trade battle between the two countries is not yet finished. local newspapers, with dispatches from washington, said u.s. officials indicated they would ask taiwan to further appreciate its currency after the one-month state mourning period for president chiang ching-kuo, who died jan. 13 of heart failure
the local media also have reported that u.s. agricultural officials have protested against planned measures by taiwan authorities to protect local farmers against foreign competition
american airlines has sparked a new round of air fare increases by boosting some one-way coach fares by $5 and first-class tickets by $10, effective saturday, officials said
delta, united and braniff airlines are among those who matched the increases that american said wednesday would affect most tickets except advance-purchase fares, the cheapest available for air travel
we felt that a slight, upward fare adjustment was economically justified at this time,'' american spokesman al becker said at the company's headquarters here
houston-based continental, which in the past year has served as the industry's price leader, matched the fare hikes in a few markets, said company spokesman doug birdsall
he said continental will continue studying the markets where it has not yet raised fares
the higher prices will affect mostly business travelers and people traveling because of a personal emergency or some other spur-of-the-moment reason, officials said
the price increases will affect:
_many coach and first-class fares for non-stop flights between major cities, including dallas, new york, chicago, kansas city, denver, san francisco and los angeles
_most unrestricted _ and unadvertised _ one-way discount fares
_some round-trip discount fares with advance-purchase requirements of up to 14 days and cancellation penalties of up to 50 percent
american's higher fares will mean, for example, that an unrestricted coach ticket to los angeles or washington, d.c., from dallas will cost $410 one way instead of $405. a discounted, unrestricted coach ticket will cost $214 on those routes, up from $209
j.c. penney co. inc. on thursday reported an increase in its fourth quarter profit despite a slight drop in sales, while another major retailer, carter hawley hale stores inc., said it had stronger second quarter earnings
penney, based in new york, said net income for the three months ended jan. 30 rose 10 percent, to $280 million, or $1.93 a share, from $253 million, or $1.80, during the same period a year ago
sales totaled $4.94 billion, down from $4.98 billion
for its fiscal year, the giant retailer's net income totaled $608 million, or $4.11 a share, on sales of $15.33 billion. that compared with earnings of $478 million, or $3.53, and sales of $14.74 billion
los angeles-based carter hawley netted $20.4 million, or 94 cents per share, on sales of $866 million for the three months ended jan. 30. a year ago, it lost $24.2 million on sales of $995.1 million, reflecting a major restructuring
the company earned $31.1 million, or $1.33 per share, during the first half of its fiscal year, vs. a deficit of $7.8 million in the previous year. sales fell to $1.48 billion from $1.7 billion
penney chairman william r. howell said the company's retail operations achieved record results during 1987 despite fierce competition during the lucrative christmas holiday season. the company's catalog operations also were especially strong throughout the year, he said
howell said penney was able to cut many expenses during the fiscal year, particularly in personnel and advertising. as a result of the 1986 tax law, income taxes were cut by $17 million in the fourth quarter, he said
howell said the company was ``well positioned to respond to consumer buying patterns'' in 1988
the expansion of women's apparel offerings and the continued strengthening of men's and children's apparel will result in significant opportunities for stores and catalog,'' he said in a statement
carter hawley's results for last year included a loss of $29.3 million in both the quarter and half for early retirement of debt, although this year's results reflected sharly higher interest payments because of debt linked to its restructuring
as part of the restructuring, the company spun off its higher-end specialty-store operations. it also sold its john wanamaker chain and two broadway-southwest stores in august 1987
carter hawley's stores include broadway, emporium capwell, thalheimers and weinstock's department stores
mississippi police are investigating allegations that american tobacco co. tampered with the jury in a cigarette liability case that ended in a mistrial last month, the los angeles times reported thursday
at issue are allegations that two employees of american's legal defense team contacted three jurors during the trial, frank carlton, district attorney for mississippi's 4th judicial district, told the times
carlton said if the contacts did occur, they probably were improper but not ``an outright attempt to ... affect the outcome of the trial.''
the allegations were made in affidavits gathered by attorneys for the family of nathan h. horton, who died at age 50 of lung cancer after smoking american's pall mall cigarettes for more than 30 years
horton's family filed a $16.5 million suit in lexington, mass., against the cigarette maker. the suit ended in a hung jury jan. 29
in the affidavits, two jurors said they were called during the trial by employees of american tobacco's legal team and and told of a change in scheduling. other affidavits said an american tobacco adviser boasted of receiving $2,700 for his work and was seen talking to a third juror
the company's lead lawyer, james upshaw, termed the affidavits ``absurb'' and ``an absolutely pathetic effort to get some type of publicity.''
grain and soybean futures closed mostly lower thursday in a modest sell-off on the chicago board of trade
soybeans led the decline in reaction to reduced demand for soybean meal, analysts said. many traders also took profits after wednesday's sharp advance in soybean futures, analysts said
increased farmer selling of soybeans also pressured futures prices, but the losses were limited by news of new soybean oil sales to india and expectations for more export business, said richard loewy, an analyst in new york for prudential-bache securities inc
based on the profit-taking which could have ensued, you're still looking at good underlying strength'' in the soybean market, loewy said
corn prices followed soybeans lower, while wheat prices retreated on expectations of adequate near-term supplies, he said
at the close, wheat was { cent to 5\ cents lower with the contract for delivery in march at $3.22{ a bushel; corn was unchanged to 1{ cents lower with march at $2.00} a bushel; oats were \ cent lower to { cent higher with march at $1.91} a bushel; soybeans were 4 cents to 6 cents lower with march at $6.28 a bushel
chemlawn services corp., the ohio-based lawn care service, uses ``fraudulent, deceptive and illegal'' advertising regarding pesticide safety, the state attorney charged wednesday in a lawsuit calling for a halt to the ads and a fine for false advertising
the lawsuit, filed in manhattan state supreme court, charged chemlawn advertising made claims ``not supported by scientific evidence or valid in only a narrow, technical sense.''
the filing by attorney general robert abrams came three weeks after chemlawn filed suit against the attorney general over his allegations and asked a supreme court judge to determine whether the advertising was misleading
the company and abrams have been arguing for months over the contents of chemlawn advertising; the attorney general notified the company in november of his impending lawsuit
we have a right to distribute accurate information about our product,'' said steve hardymon, a chemlawn spokesman. ``the attorney general has been harassing us for the last year. we just got tired of it, and asked a judge to make the final decision on the ads.''
hardymon had not seen abrams' filing wednesday, and could not comment on his specific charges
the attorney general alleged that because information is not available about the chronic, long-term effects of many pesticides, chemlawn could not guarantee full safety
abrams specifically cited one ad as false and misleading after it promised, ``a person would have to ingest over 40 cupfuls of lawn clippings treated with chemlawn to equal the toxicity of a single cup of coffee.''
the stock market showed no clear trend today, continuing the sluggish pattern of wednesday's session
