stock-index futures retreated on the chicago mercantile exchange, where the contract for march delivery of the standard &amp; poor's 500 index settled 1.55 points lower at 258.30. the underlying spot index was up 1.30 points at 257.91. with m2 and m3 figures. picks up 6th graf pvs, the fed...</note>
the nation's basic money supply fell by $3.4 billion in mid-february, the federal reserve board reported thursday
the fed said the measure of money known as m1 fell to a seasonally adjusted $760.7 billion in the week ended feb. 8 from $764.1 billion the previous week. m1 includes cash in circulation, deposits in checking accounts and non-bank travelers checks
for the latest 13 weeks, m1 averaged $754.7 billion, a 1.9 percent seasonally adjusted annual rate of gain from the previous 13 weeks
analysts said the latest figure was within the range expected by a number of economists, and as such had little effect on the bond market
the fed last year stopped setting a specific growth target range for m1 because of doubts that the measurement accurately reflected underlying economic activity. instead, the fed indicated, it was more closely monitoring broader monetary aggregates known as m2 and m3, exchange rates and other economic indicators
on thursday, the fed began reporting m2 and m3 on a weekly instead of monthly basis. m2 fell $1.8 billion in the week ended feb. 8 to a seasonally-adjusted $2.94 trillion, and m3 fell $2.1 billion to an adjusted $3.712 trillion
m2 is made up of m1 and such accounts as savings deposits and money-market mutual funds. m3 is the sum of m2 plus less-liquid accounts, such as certificates of deposit in minimum denominations of $100,000
the fed on thursday also released its benchmark revisions to the monetary aggregates for 1987
the central bank said m1 growth in 1987 was 6.2 percent, revised from 5.9 percent; m2 growth was 4.0 percent, revised from 4.1 percent, and m3 growth was unrevised at 5.4 percent
the fed had set a growth target range of 5.5 percent to 8.5 percent for m2 and m3. the actual growth was the slowest in those aggregates since the fed began targeting growth in 1979
in other reports:
_the federal reserve bank of new york reported commercial and industrial loans at major new york city banks fell $368 million in the week ended feb. 10, compared with a gain of $87 million a week earlier
_the federal reserve said discount window bank borrowings from the federal reserve system averaged $254 million daily in the week ended wednesday, up from $118 million during the previous week
_the federal reserve bank of st. louis reported that the monetary base, the seasonally adjusted total of member bank reserves held at federal reserve banks and cash in bank vaults and in circulation, was $272.4 billion in the two-week period ended feb. 10, down from $272.9 billion two weeks earlier
the farm credit system said it earned a profit of $179 million in the final quarter of 1987, but posted a loss for the full year in spite of a big reduction in its reserve for loan losses
the loss of $17 million for all of 1987 was a fraction of the losses of $2.7 billion in 1985 and $1.9 billion in 1986
the farm credit system said its interest income fell because of competition from other lenders and a general decline in the demand for agricultural loans. on the positive side, the system said it was able to reduce the amount of money set aside for possible loan losses because of ``continued improvement in the general agricultural economy and the increased capacity of farmers and ranchers to service their debt.''
loan-loss reserves were decreased by $684 million during the year, to $2.95 billion at the end of 1987 from $3.64 billion at the end of 1986
the farm credit system is a 71-year-old group of 37 banking cooperatives and nearly 400 local lending associations. it was hit hard by weakness in the agricultural economy
bailout legislation signed into law last year created a private assistance corporation that is authorized to issue up to $4 billion in government-backed loans to financially troubled institutions in the system
interest on the loans will be paid initially by the government, although the farm credit system would eventually pay everything back
the farm credit system said its profit of $179 million in the fourth quarter came on total interest income of $1.46 billion. in the year-earlier period, the system had a loss of $384 million on total interest income of $1.65 billion
in all of 1987, the farm credit system's loss of $17 million came on total interest income of $5.78 billion, in contrast to a year-earlier loss of $1.91 billion on total interest income of $7.17 billion
the strong fourth-quarter results are not indicative of expectations for 1988, the farm credit system said, because they include a chunk of interest income from previous periods that was not previously recorded
the results were also boosted by one-time reductions in loan-loss provisions
the reduction in the provision for loan losses, partly offset by some actual losses, added $207 million to the system's bottom line in the fourth quarter and added $196 million to the bottom line in all of 1987
in contrast, new provision for loan losses had subtracted $356 million from the bottom line in the fourth quarter of 1986 and subtracted $1.80 billion from the bottom line in all of 1986
price waterhouse, the system's independent accountants, issued an opinion on the statement that was qualified because of questions surrounding the implementation of the federal bailout
the successful and timely implementation of the 1987 act is dependent on several factors, many of which are outside the control of the system,'' the farm credit system said in a news release
the teamsters union is girding for a worldwide strike against pan am corp. on sunday, but some travel agents say the troubled airline's incentives will keep passengers lining up at the gate
in formally announcing strike plans at a press conference thursday, william genoese, director of the union's airline division, promised a ``traditional type'' of teamster walkout
separately, the airline announced it lost $265.3 million last year, compared with a $462.8 million loss the previous year. the airline, which earlier estimated it lost $90 million last year, reiterated in the earnings statement its pledge to remain fully operational in the event of a strike
genoese said there is enough support for pan am local 732 among other teamsters locals to cut off the airline's supplies of fuel, laundry and liquor around the world. and he added that there will be violence ``if the company provokes violence.''
the strike is set to begin at 12:01 a.m. est sunday, the end of a federally mandated 30-day cooling-off period in the labor dispute
several travel agents polled thursday said the public is barely aware of the conflict, which centers on the teamsters' demand for higher pay and the airline's call for belt-tightening
the 4,500-member pan am teamsters local represents passenger reservation clerks, customer service employees and workers who fuel planes
thomas g. plaskett, pan am's new chairman, told union members in a letter earlier this month that in the event of a strike, the airline ``can and will hire someone to provide the services you withhold.''
pan am spokeswoman pamela hanlon said the carrier already has recruited potential replacement employees and trained managers within the company to perform some of the teamsters' clerical functions
the teamsters have yet to receive a show of support from pan am's four other unions. jim gannon, a spokesman for the 5,000-member transport workers union, said members voted unanimously thursday against supporting the teamsters
and a spokesman for the airline's flight engineers said members were advised to ``continue with their work assignments.'' the pilots and flight attendants unions also are not expected to support the teamsters
the pilots, flight attendants and engineers already have accepted labor concessions in an effort to ensure pan am's financial recovery
herbert teison, of travel smart for business in dobbs ferry, n.y., said most travelers ``don't even know about the strike.''
and jack bloch, president of jb's world travel in new york, said he hasn't seen any cancellations yet. ``their frequent-flier program, their special fares that are lower than most other carriers and their triple mileage offer keeps people choosing money over service,'' he said
pan am had no comment on a teamsters claim that the carrier has begun installing armed guards throughout its facilities at new york's john f. kennedy international airport, the airline's main hub
obviously security is a top priority,'' hanlon said. ``we are making preparations to deal with it, but we won't disclose what they may be.''
genoese said the hiring of the guards was a provocation that by itself could spark violence among members
the teamsters, pan am and meredith buel, a spokesman for the national mediation board in washington, d.c., acknowledge that negotiations are still going on. but genoese said no progress has been made and he remains pessimistic
picketing is expected to begin sunday morning, and several rallies have been scheduled at hotels near jfk airport
our people are all positioned, they have signs and they know where to go,'' said frank bertucelli, business representative for local 732
pan am, which operates pan american world airways inc., a northeast air shuttle and other services, needs labor concessions totaling around $540 million over three years to ensure its survival, analysts and company sources estimate
the teamsters say they have offered $75 million in concessions over the next three years. pan am has sought an 8 percent wage cut per year, work rule changes and revisions to its health care plan
the teamsters claim that the give-backs amount to a 15 percent to 17 percent wage cut for members, who make an average $480 a week and have not received a raise since 1981
last month plaskett last month rejected an offer from the national mediation board to arbitrate the contract dispute with the teamsters
by rejecting arbitration, plaskett set in motion a federally mandated 30- day ``cooling-off'' period between the two sides. at the end of that time, pan am would be free to impose its demands on the union, which in turn would be free to strike
gov. william donald schaefer signed into law thursday bills giving top corporate officials greater protection from lawsuits filed by disgruntled stockholders
schaefer had sought the legislation to enhance the state's business climate and to prevent some maryland-based companies from moving their headquarters to neighboring states that offer such protection to officers and directors
as of jan. 1, some 35 states had enacted laws offering some degree of immunity from stockholder suits and are actively using such laws to sell their states to companies considering reincorporation, said alan rifkin, schaefer's top legislative aide
this says something to business,'' schaefer said as he signed two identical bills passed at morning sessions of both the house and senate
it says we're interested in working together for the good of the state,'' he said
the measures are specifically aimed at lawsuits brought by stockholders who believe a business decision by an officer or director was responsible for a drop in the value of a company's stock
business leaders strongly supported the measures, telling lawmakers that skyrocketing liability insurance premiums have made it increasingly difficult to attract quality business people to serve on boards of directors
the schaefer administration introduced a bill for the same purpose last year, but it was rejected by the house judiciary committee, reportedly because 1987's version did not give stockholders the right to reject such immunity for its officers and directors
the bill signed thursday requires formal ratification of the immunity provision by stockholders. the law also specifies that such protection does not apply to lawsuits brought by third parties
under the new law, which went into effect immediately after schaefer signed the bills, such immunity is lost when an officer or director receives an improper financial benefit or in cases involving deliberate dishonesty by a top corporate official
the reagan administration, proposing a $1.1 trillion federal budget on thursday, predicted the economy would continue to grow without threat of recession
in other economic news, the federal reserve said the nation's industrial operating rate was unchanged in january at 82.2 percent of capacity, remaining at the highest level in almost eight years
in the financial markets, the stock market gave ground in late trading thursday and the dow jones average of 30 industrials dropped below 2,000, falling 14.58 to 1,986.41. bond prices and the dollar edged higher
in its 1989 budget request, the administration foresaw no storm clouds on the economic horizon, contending growth would slow during the first half of 1988 but then rebound to robust levels in 1989 and beyond
the administration's economic forecasts, which provide the underpinning for its assumptions on revenues and spending in the budget, have been attacked in the past as rosy scenarios which bore little resemblance to reality
but this year's version was greeted with less skepticism, although it was still more optimistic than the outlook prepared by the congressional budget office and most private economists
in the last couple of years, the administration has lightened the tint on their rose-colored glasses although their outlook is still a lot rosier than we think is justified,'' said david wyss, an economist with data resources inc., an economic forecasting firm
the administration derided as greatly exaggerated recession fears stirred by the record 508-point drop in the new york stock exchange's dow jones industrial average on oct. 19 and contended the economy had escaped with ``few signs of serious damage.''
the administration predicted the gross national product, the total output of goods and services, would expand at a modest rate of 2.4 percent this year, down from 3.8 percent growth in 1987, when measured from the fourth quarter of 1986
congressional analysts are forecasting lower growth of 1.8 percent in 1988 and wyss said data resources has just scaled back its own gnp forecast to 1.4 percent, a full percentage point below the administration
in the capacity utilization report, the federal reserve said cutbacks in the production of steel and autos offset gains in other areas, the government reported thursday
the january operating rate remained at the highest level in almost eight years, but it was the first month since september that the operating rate had failed to move up
international business machines corp., which has assembled an ensemble of actors from the ``m-a-s-h'' television series for its advertising, said thursday it has signed the star of that popular program
ibm said that alan alda, who starred as hawkeye pierce in ``m-a-s-h,'' signed a multiyear agreement earlier this month to appear in commercials for the computer and office systems giant
the company declined to disclose how much alda was being paid
the first ads featuring alda will appear saturday during abc-tv's olympics broadcasts, ibm said. he will initially appear alone in ibm ads
in one commercial, alda paddles about a flooded office and describes how an ibm service team worked without stop to restore a customer's computer operations
he says ibm can help customers face the future in another ad, and describes in a third commercial how the company can help businesses of all sizes
dave mcgovern, an advertising executive for ibm, said the company eventually plans to work alda into ads that feature other former members of the ``m-a-s-h'' cast
ibm launched advertising for its new family of personal system 2 computers featuring seven former ``m-a-s-h'' cast members last april, including gary burghoff who played radar o'reilly, harry morgan who was col. sherman potter and loretta swit who played hot lips houlihan. for ibm, they played the roles of co-workers in an office
conspicuously absent from that group was alda, who reportedly was still under contract to another computer company, atari corp
mcgovern said ibm had been interested in having alda appear in its ads for some time, but that alda had other commitments that were preventing it
a call was placed to alda's agent, but was not returned
mcgovern said alda continues to be widely recognized and is well liked by the public although the ``m-a-s-h'' program creators and actors have disbanded and the show has gone into reruns
he said alda has done little advertising and said his appearances for atari occurred five years ago and should not diminish his effectiveness for ibm
you don't have a sense that he is saying anything he doesn't believe in,'' said barry hoffman, a creative director for the ad agency lord, geller, federico, einstein inc., which created the ibm ads
mcgovern said the ads using the former ``m-a-s-h'' actors have scored better than the industry average with the public
ibm has said that it did not set out to reassemble the ``m-a-s-h'' cast for its ads. among those from that program who are missing from the ibm ensemble are mclean stevenson, who played col. henry blake
mcgovern declined to speculate on whether any new characters would be added to the ibm ads. ``stay tuned for further developments,'' he said
pan am corp. said thursday it lost $245.5 million in the 1987 fourth quarter and $265.3 million for the year, blaming the results on labor costs, poor marketing, uncollectable bills and the airline's frequent-flier program
at the same time, usair group inc., one of the nation's fastest-growing airlines, reported slightly lower fourth-quarter earnings but record earnings for the year, during which it acquired two other carriers
pan am's losses, reported against a background of labor-management feuding, an executive shakeup and an impending strike this weekend, bring the venerable airline company's losses to more than $883 million in the past four years
the quarterly loss was 24 percent higher than the $197.5 million loss in the same quarter of 1986, although the yearly loss was about 43 percent lower than the 1986 loss of $462.8 million. still, pan am officials expressed alarm
last year's results are terribly disappointing for the company,'' said thomas g. plaskett, who was elected chairman of pan am last month
a loss of this magnitude underscores the urgent need for pan am to lower its current operating costs and revitalize its marketing and revenue-generating programs,'' plaskett said in a statement
fourth-quarter revenues totaled $877.1 million, up 9.8 percent from $798.6 million in the same quarter of 1986. for the year, revenues totaled $3.59 billion, up 18.2 percent from $3.04 billion in 1986
aside from blaming labor costs, which are among the highest in the industry, pan am said the losses last year were aggravated by $42 million in ``increased allowances for inventory obsolescence, uncollectible receivables, and costs associated with the worldpass frequent-flier program.''
such programs, offered by all major carriers, attempt to gain repeat customers by offering them free trips after they fly a certain number of miles. usair group said its 1987 fourth-quarter earnings totaled $26.7 million or 62 cents a share, a 16.6 percent drop from the $32 million or $1.06 a share reported a year earlier. the company had 43.19 million shares outstanding in the 1987 quarter vs. 31.73 million a year earlier
quarterly revenues totaled $1.12 billion, more than double the $483.38 million reported a year earlier
for all of 1987, usair said it earned a record $194.64 million or $5.28 a share, nearly double the $98.35 million or $3.34 a share earned in 1986. revenues totaled a record $3 billion vs. $1.83 billion, a 63.5 percent gain
usair group is an airline holding company that includes usair, pacific southwest airlines and piedmont aviation. psa was acquired in may 1987 and piedmont was purchased in november 1987
the company said its financial statement reflected the consolidated results of all three airlines for the months following the acquisitions, as well as usair's equity stake in piedmont prior to the completion of that acquisition. less for defense</head> expand on relationship of deficit numbers to gramm-rudman law; also moved on general newswires</note>
president reagan proposed thursday his smallest pentagon increase but sharply higher spending for aids research and airline safety in a $1.1 trillion fiscal 1989 budget that was largely pre-ordained in a deal with congress
this budget does not fully reflect my priorities,'' the president said in his message accompanying the last spending plan he'll see through to completion. ``but ... abandoning the deficit reduction compromise would threaten our economic progress and burden future generations.''
the spending plan only hints of the ``reagan revolution'' years as it strives to comply with the administration's agreement with congressional leaders last november to reduce the federal deficit
the agreement set overall spending limits for domestic, military and foreign aid spending. reagan has already signed the tax increase required under the agreement, adding $14 billion to the treasury's receipts for next year
the president's plan envisions overall spending of $1.094 trillion, offset by $965 billion in receipts. that would leave a deficit of about $129.5 billion in the fiscal year beginning oct. 1, within the guidelines of the gramm-rudman, budget-balancing law and down from $150.4 billion last year and an estimated $146 billion this year
because of the agreement with congressional leaders, reagan was forced for the first time to submit a military budget that would not keep pace with inflation
restrained to $294 billion in outlays, up from $285.4 billion this year, the president proposed reducing the nation's active-duty forces and abandoning the goal of a 600-ship navy
servicemen and women would get a 4.3 percent pay increase, compared to 2 percent for other federal employees
on the domestic side of the ledger, the president requested new spending authority that he has resisted in the past but which congress would likely favor anyway in an election year, including:
_$1.3 billion for aids research, a 38 percent increase
_an increase of $1.5 billion, or 8 percent, on education
_a 13 percent boost, to $3.9 billion, for drug law enforcement and treatment programs
_$363 million to begin construction of the superconducting super collider, a huge new atomic research facility
_full funding for a $2.5 billion, five-year program to combat acid rain, and an increase in spending on hazardous waste cleanup
_a 44 percent increase, to $1.6 billion, for the federal aviation administration to modernize its air traffic control system
_$11.5 billion for space programs, including the manned space station and space shuttle improvements. the actual outlay would be $10.9 billion in 1989
but reagan offsets those increases by calling for an halt to amtrak and mass transit subsidies, ending urban development action grants, and eliminating the interstate commerce commission and economic development administration. in addition, government assets such as loan portfolios, the alaska power administration and the naval petroleum reserve would be sold
the president's budget director, james c. miller iii, told reporters that, even though congress has rejected many reagan budget proposals like asset sales in the past, he believed they would fare better this time
congress will have to come up with these additional savings one way or another,'' miller said, suggesting that the cuts outlined in reagan's budget might be ``the course of least resistance for congress.''
treasury secretary james a. baker iii said it was ``the intention of both the executive and legislative branches to honestly fulfill the terms of the budget agreement. it's a rather unique budget year.''
reagan said his budget reflected the give-and-take of last fall's budget ``summit.''
in presenting this budget, i am keeping my end of the bargain. i call upon congress to uphold its end,'' he said
house majority leader thomas s. foley, d-wash., said congress would live within the agreement but ``there is obviously room for setting priorities in a different way than the president's budget proposes.''
the deputy democratic leader in the house, tony coelho of california, was less generous. he said the failure to do more to tackle the deficit leaves ``an enormous problem to the next administration and to the next generation. it is a sad closing chapter to the failed story of reaganomics.''
the administration predicts that if its budget is adopted deficits would continue to retreat from the record levels earlier in reagan's term. when reagan took office in 1981, the annual deficit was $78 billion, and he promised to bring the budget into balance within three years. instead annual deficits nearly tripled by fiscal 1986
to stay below the $136 billion deficit target for fiscal 1989 in the gramm-rudman law, the budget includes $10 billion in revenue from selling government assets and other one-time receipts
but those sales aren't counted in gramm-rudman's calculations, because they are only temporary solutions. so the president technically failed to hit the $136 billion target, although not by the $10 billion margin that would trigger automatic spending cuts
the goals for future years are missed by the plan even by the president's own estimates
rep. dan rostenkowski, d-ill., chairman of the house ways and means committee, said he doubted either the white house or congress would face up to the continuing deficit problem this year. ``this is the year of the big wink,'' he said. ``i don't envy the president who will follow this administration because of the deficit he will inherit.''
the administration figures are based on projections that economic growth will continue undiminished by last fall's stock market collapse, and that inflation will ease
gnp growth will rebound in 1989 to a 3.5 percent rate and stay above 3 percent through 1993, according to the budget. consumer prices, which rose 4.4 percent last year, will rise by 4.3 percent this year. the jobless rate of 5.8 percent will hold steady, according to the budget
the forecast is more optimstic than that of the congressional budget office and private economists, but not so far out of line with them as in past years
the chairmen of the house and senate budget committees said they thought reagan's budget was more realistic than his past efforts
i think it's a good faith budget,'' said sen. lawton chiles, d-fla., chairman of the senate committee
what we're doing now is working together,'' said william h. gray iii, d-pa., the house chairman. ``the president and the congress compromised.''
sen. ernest f. hollings, d-s.c., a member of the budget committee and co-sponsor of the gramm-rudman law, said the administration's deficit projections might be too optimistic, but ``no one's going to talk about it.''
the administration said if growth was even one percentage point less than reagan's forecast, the deficit would rise an additional $6.3 billion in 1989 and $18 billion in 1990
but hollings predicted this year's battles will be over the details, not the overall thrust of the budget or its deficit-reduction goals
it's like tying two cats by the tail and throwing them over the clothesline,'' he said. ``there'll be a lot of small intramurals, but nothing really's going to happen.'' with nab response; inserts 2 grafs after 13th graf bgng: charren said ... to add mattel response. picks up 14th graf pvs bgng: markey said ...; also moved on general newswires</note>
children's television advocates in the house and senate introduced legislation thursday designed to rid the airwaves of programs that feature toy manufacturers' products as the central characters
children's tv has been grossly overcommercialized,'' said sen. howard metzenbaum, d-ohio, sponsor of the senate measure. ``you flip the dial and you'll find toys _ lady lovelylocks, thundercats, inhumanoids, gi joe _ all starring in their own shows.''
since the federal communications commission in 1984 scrapped its commercial limits on children's tv shows, at least 70 programs that critics call ``program-length commercials'' have appeared on television, he said
such programs are nothing more than ``sophisticated marketing strategies aimed at kids,'' he said
i just say that's absurd and it's wrong. the airwaves belong to the people of this country and they're being abused,'' he said at a news conference attended by other members of the house and senate and organized by action for children's television
the legislation was attacked by the national association of broadcasters, which called it ``anachronistic, unnecessary, inappropriate and ineffective,'' and said it raises first amendment questions
the nab said toy-based programs are not commercials and not subject to government regulation. ``does the federal government want to eliminate the disney, sesame street and charlie brown programs?'' nab said
metzenbaum's bill would restore the fcc's previous guidelines that limited ads on children's shows to 9{ minutes per hour on weekends and 12 minutes per hour on weekdays
a similar house bill also would reinstate the limits and in addition would require tv stations to provide seven hours per week of educational programming for young viewers
we can make children's television better,'' said rep. terry bruce, d-ill., who co-sponsored the house measure with reps. john bryant, d-texas, and edward markey, d-mass., chairman of the house telecommunications subcommittee
the fcc, in response to a federal appeals court ruling last june, is reviewing its children's tv policies and is considering whether ad limits are needed and whether toy-based shows constitute program-length commercials
but markey said congress will not wait for the fcc to act
the commission clearly has demonstrated that it cannot be trusted to protect children from commercial exploitation,'' said markey, who has crossed swords with the fcc over many broadcasting issues. ``when it comes to children's programming, this commission has never found an offensive practice that it did not like.''
charren said her group has been concerned for years that commercial considerations dominate programming decisions regarding children's tv, making it difficult to get stations to devote time to educational and informational shows for kids
spencer boise, a vice president of mattel inc., which makes a dozen different toys on which cartoon shows are based, said the programs are not commercials because the toys themselves are not shown and ads for the toys never appear during or adjacent to the program featuring the toy's cartoon character
it's an entertainment concept,'' he said. ``the characters are shown in cartoon or animated form, not static form like the toys.''
markey said the content of many of the toy-based programs for children would be classified as commercial time and, with ad limitations in place, would be driven off the air
there will be certain clear areas where it will be indisputably evident to all who witness it that a seamless fabric connecting commercials to program content has been developed,'' he said
we may reach some gray areas where there is a more open question, but clearly there is going to be an overwhelming consensus in the bulk of the areas ... that will be very difficult for anyone to deny that products are actually seeking to be promoted as part of the program content,'' he said
a former trw inc. executive entered a guilty plea to a charge of conspiracy to make false statements and submit false documents to the defense department, the justice department announced thursday
patrick m. mclaughlin, u.s. attorney for the northern district of ohio, said the government had alleged that richard e. kavicky, former financial manager of trw's compressor components division, conspired with other trw employees
u.s. district judge george w. white accepted the plea and allowed kavicky to remain free on personal bond pending completion of a pre-sentence report
last week, kavicky, 55, of wickliffe, ohio, agreed to cooperate with a federal investigation of trw's handling of federal contracts
president reagan proposed his smallest pentagon increase but sharply higher spending for aids research and airline safety in a $1.1 trillion fiscal 1989 budget
the spending plan revealed on thursday only hints of the ``reagan revolution'' years as it strives to comply with the administration's agreement with congressional leaders last november to reduce the federal deficit
president reagan's 1989 budget proposal calls for a 5 percent cut in agriculture spending, including sharp reductinos for two major rural development agencies
but the budget packaged unveiled thursday does not call for new legislation or cuts in most farm commodity programs. officials said the one major exception will be an administration attempt to overhaul the u.s. sugar program, which includes protective import quotas and price supports
president reagan asked congress for a new tax break to help parents finance a college education for their children
in a budget recommending only a few tax changes, reagan called thursday for requiring all state and local government employees to pay a tax for medicare coverage. he proposed a permanent tax benefit for owners of shares in mutual funds and an expanded break for independent oil producers
the reagan administration said the economy was shrugging off the impact of the october stock market collapse and would enjoy modest growth this presidential election year with no threat of a recession
in its 1989 budget request released thursday, the administration foresaw no storm clouds on the economic horizon, contending that growth would slow during the first half of 1988 but then rebound to robust levels in 1989 and beyond
the administration predicted the gross national product, the total output of goods and services, would expand at a modest rate of 2.4 percent this year, down from 3.8 percent growth in 1987, when measured from the fourth quarter of 1986
the nation's industrial operating rate was unchanged in january at 82.2 percent of capacity as cutbacks in the production of steel and autos offset gains in other areas
the january operating rate reported by the government thursday remained at the highest level in almost eight years, but it was the first month since september that the operating rate had failed to move up. some economists suggested this provided further evidence of an impending slowdown
ford motor co.'s earnings jumped 19 percent in the fourth quarter and 41 percent for all of 1987 as the no. 2 automaker outearned general motors corp. for the second straight year
the results announced thursday were good news to ford workers, who will earn record profit-sharing checks, but some experts on wall street had expected even better earnings from the company
after the earnings announcement, ford's stock fell, finishing down $2.25 per share to $42.25 on the new york stock exchange
a majority of striking employees at ford motor co.'s british plants voted to accept a two-year contract offer, signaling the end of the country's first major industrial strike in three years
the offer represented the first significant union victory in britain in seven years. ford made several concessions to end the strike, which began feb. 8
voter returns thursday night showed 70 percent of the workers at the 22 british plants favored the offer. the company said it expected workers to be back on the job monday
texaco inc. plans to sell a stake of about 50 percent in its extensive u.s. gulf coast refining operations to saudi arabia for more than $1 billion, according to published reports
a final agreement between petromin, the saudi arabian oil holding arm, and texaco is expected to be reached within a month, the herald tribune reported thursday, quoting an unidentified texaco executive and unidentified arab oil executives attending an annual conference of the institute of petroleum in london
in white plains, n.y., a spokesman at texaco's headquarters refused to confirm or deny the accuracy of the report
american standard inc.'s board of directors approved a multibillion-dollar recapitalization plan, escalating the company's battle to thwart the hostile $2.03 billion takeover bid by black &amp; decker corp
the plan approved thursday would pay american standard stockholders $64 a share in cash and junk bonds and give them stock in the recapitalized company, which would take on a staggering new debt load to finance the proposal
american standard shares rose 50 cents to $67.50 and black &amp; decker dipped 12{ cents to $18.87{ on the new york stock exchange
severe insider-trading penalties are damaging new cases by discouraging potential defendants from cooperating, a top official of the securities and exchange commission was quoted as saying
gary lynch, sec enforcement director and one of the architects behind a campaign against wall street corruption, was quoted as saying in a television interview that the prospect of imprisonment, civil fines and financial ruin is convincing some people ``it's better to hunker down than cooperate.'' his remarks were to be broadcast sunday on ``the wall street journal report.''
federal regulators have ordered an immediate suspension of the use of an industrial device which has leaked tiny particles of radioactive polonium at plants around the nation
the nuclear regulatory commission also ordered the 3m corp. on thursday to recall for inspection all 45,000 of the suspect devices, ionizing air guns used to control static electricity and remove dust from product containers
stocks declined in late trading thursday. the dow jones industrial average dropped 14.58 points to 1,986.41 after closing slightly above 2,000 in the week's first two sessions
bond prices rose in reaction to falling commodity prices. the dollar closed lower in europe but higher in the united states. gold prices were mostly down
southland corp. officials said thursday they have reached an agreement to sell the dallas-based company's dairies group to morningstar foods inc. for an undisclosed amount
the purchase by morningstar, an affiliate of houston-based private investment firm duncan, cook &amp; co., will include 10 regional dairies located throughout the united states, comprising 25 plants and related distribution points
morningstar expects to retain substantially all dairies group employees. also, the dairies will continue to operate under their own recognized brand names, including adohr farms, bancroft, cabell's, embassy, high's, merritt foods, oak farms, specialty products, velda farms and wanzer
the sale of the dairies group is one of several previously announced in connection with the december 1987 leveraged buyout of southland by jt acquisition corp., an affiliate of thompson co., the investment firm of southland's founding family
in a leveraged buyout, the purchaser puts up as collateral money that will be generated from the sale of the target company's assets
in addition to the recently completed sale of 270 7-eleven stores in houston, southland has reached agreements to sell its chief auto parts, moviequik videocassette rental and tidel systems operations and 21 7-eleven stores in missouri
the company also plans to divest its reddy ice, snack foods and chemical-food labs divisions and about 700 other convenience stores
the dairies group has played an important role in southland's growth and the success of our 7-eleven stores since 1936, when the oak farms dairy was founded in dallas,'' said jere thompson, president of southland
southland is the nation's largest convenience retailer, with 8,000 7-eleven and other convenience stores supported by five southland distribution centers and six southland foods division food centers
